  • The GDP per capita comes from The World Bank.
  • The education score comes from World Population Review.
  • The income per person comes from Kaggle.

Data management¶

Now that we have have our dataframes, we want to tidy the data to help make our future analysis more convenient. To do that, we will need to:

  • figure out a way to deal with the missing data
  • reorganize our dataframe to help with our data visualizations later

To get rid of missing data, we will use pandas.DataFrame.interpolate. By choosing the 'nearest' method we set the missing values to the nearest value.

In [3]:
# identify the missing data and set them to NaN
marriage=marriage.replace('..','NaN')
country=marriage.iloc[:,:1]
# fill the missing values using the nearest values
marriage=marriage.iloc[:,1:].astype(float).interpolate(method='nearest', axis=0).ffill().bfill()
new_marriage=country.join(marriage)
new_marriage.head()

Linear Regression and Hypothesis Testing¶

To further examine the relationship between time and marriage rate, we try to construct a linear regression model and use hypothesis testing to verify if our model fit the data well.

Our first step is to find out whether there exist a linear relationship between time and marriage rate. We already see this decreasing tread in the violin plot and scatter plot above, now we will be using Pearson correlation coefficient to see how strong is this linear relationship. Pearson correlation coefficient measures the linear correlation between two sets of data. It has a value between 1 and 1. The greater the absolute value indicates the stronger the linear relationship. A positive correlation coefficient means there exist a positive linear relationship while a negative correlation coefficient means there exist a negative linear relationship.

In [ ]:
sns.heatmap(data.corr(), annot=True, cmap='Blues')
plt.show()

Here we see that the correlation coefficient between marriage rate and Date is -0.67, which shows a relatively strong negative linear relationship. Therefore, we continue our next step to construct our linear regression model.

statsmodels.formula.api.ols creates a Model from a formula and dataframe.

In [ ]:
regression1 = ols(formula="marriage_rate~Date", data=data).fit()
regression1.summary()

Independent Var: Date

Dependent Var: marriage_rate

R-squared value = 0.445

P>|t| = 0.00

The P>|t| is the p-value for our hypothesis testing reguarding the coefficient for the intercept and independent variable.

Null Hypothesis: The value of the coefficient is not significantly different from 0.

Alternative Hypothesis: The value of the coefficient is significantly different from 0.

Since P>|t| < 0.05 (significance level), we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the coefficient value we get is significantly different from zero.

The R-squared value means 44.5% of the observed variation for marriage can be explained by Date. 44.5% is not very high, therefore we need to find a way to improve our regression model.

Recall our violin plot in the above section, the marriage rate also differs between different country. Let's take that into account and reconstruct our model.

In [ ]:
regression2 = ols(formula="marriage_rate ~ Date + Country + Date * Country", data=data).fit()
regression2.summary()

Independent Var: Date, Country

Dependent Var: marriage_rate

R-squared value = 0.748

P>|t| = 0.00

We see that the R-squared value has increase to 0.748.

In [ ]:
#Run ANOVA
result = sm.stats.anova_lm(regression1, typ=2)
result
In [ ]:
#Run ANOVA
result = sm.stats.anova_lm(regression2, typ=2)
result
